{{Portal|Anglicanism}}'''John William Hawkins Flagg''' was an [[Anglican]] [[missionary]] [[bishop]] from 1969 to 1977;<ref>Obituary, [[Daily Telegraph]] dated 17 October 2008</ref> and was later [[Secretary|General Secretary]] of the ''South American Missionary Society''. Born in [[Somerset]]<ref>From Ploughshare to Crook Flagg, J.W.H: London, Triangle, 2000 {{ISBN|0-281-05213-1}}</ref> on 16 June 1929 and ordained in 1959 <ref>[[Who's Who (UK)]]|2008: London, [[A & C Black]] {{ISBN|978-0-7136-8555-8}}</ref> he began his career with the post of  [[Chaplain]]  at  the ''St Andrew's Mission'', [[Asunción]] <ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]2008/2009 Lambeth, Church House Publishing {{ISBN|978-0-7151-1030-0}}</ref> after which he was [[Archdeacon]] of  [[Paraguay]] before his ordination to the [[episcopate]] as Northern Argentina and Paraguay's first Anglican [[bishop]]. Translated to [[Peru]]  in 1973 he returned to Britain in 1978 as [[Vicar]] of St Cyprian's, [[Edge Hill, Merseyside|Edge Hill]]<ref>During this time he was also an [[assistant bishop]] in the [[Anglican Diocese of Liverpool|Diocese of Liverpool]] > Who’s Who (ibid)</ref> before another spell in South America. He died on 1 October 2008, leaving behind six children, many grandchildren and one great grandchild.

