|image3=Shang grapheme for jǔ 矩 (capenter's square).svg|caption3=③
|image4=Shang grapheme for yāng 央 (centring).svg|caption4=④
|footer=❶ [[regular script|k]]:巫 ''[[wu (shaman)|wū]]'' — "shaman", "man who knows", the [[cross potent]] ☩ being a symbol of the ''[[magi]]'' and magic/craft also in Western cultures;<ref>{{cite book|last=Mair|first=Victor|authorlink=Victor H. Mair|chapter=The Earliest Identifiable Written Chinese Character|editor-last1=Huld|editor-first1=Martin E.|editor-last2=Jones-Bley|editor-first2=Karlene|editor-last3=Miller|editor-first3=Dean A.|title=Archaeology and Language: Indo-European Studies Presented to James P. Mallory|journal=Journal of Indo-European Studies|number=60|publisher=Institute for the Study of Man|year=2012|issn=0895-7258|isbn=0984538356|pages=265–279}}</ref><br>❷ [[regular script|k]]:方 ''fāng'' — "square", "phase", "direction", "power" and other meanings of ordering, which was used interchangeably with the grapheme ''wu'';<br>❸ [[regular script|k]]:矩 ''jǔ'' — "carpenter's square";<br>❹ [[regular script|k]]:央 ''yāng'' — "centring".<br>All of them contain the rod element signifying the square tool, used to make right angles. According to David W. Pankenier, the same staff is the horizontal line in the grapheme 帝 ''dì'', "deity" or "emperor".{{sfnb|Pankenier|2013|pp=112–113}}}}

So, human beings participate in the ongoing creation-evolution of the God of Heaven, acting as ancestors who may produce and influence other beings:{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|pp=131–132}}
{{Quote|The involvement of an evolution in the divine creation hints that, although the Creator functions everywhere and all the time, every little creation is also participated by one particular thing which was previously created by the Creator. That is to say, each creature plays both the roles of creature and creator, and consequently is not only a fixed constituent of, but also a promoter and author of, the diversity or richness of the world.}}

[[File:Luna-Reflection-Sea-Superluna-Night-Super-Water-1826849.jpg|thumb|left|The metaphor of the moon.]]

The relationship between oneness and multiplicity, between the supreme principle and the myriad things, is notably explained by Zhu Xi through the "metaphor of the moon":{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|pp=188–190}}
{{Quote|Fundamentally there is only one Great Pole (''Tàijí''), yet each of the myriad things has been endowed with it and each in itself possesses the Great Ultimate in its entirety. This is similar to the fact that there is only one moon in the sky, but when its light is scattered upon rivers and lakes, it can be seen everywhere. It cannot be said that the moon has been split.}}

In his terminology, the myriad things are generated as effects or actualities (用 ''yòng'') of the supreme principle, which, before in potence (體 ''tǐ''), sets in motion ''qi''. The effects are different, forming the "myriad species" (萬殊 ''wànshū''), each relying upon their myriad modifications of the principle, depending on the varying contexts and engagements. Difference exists not only between the various categories of beings, but among individuals belonging to the same category as well, so that each creature is a unique coalescence of the cosmic principle.{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|pp=188–190}} The ''qi'' of kindred beings accord and communicate with one another, and the same happens for the ''qi'' of worshippers and the god receiving sacrifice, and for the ''qi'' of an ancestor and his descendants.{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|p=200}} All beings are, at different levels, "in" the God of Heaven, not in the sense of addition but in the sense of belonging.{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|p=212}}

In the Confucian tradition, the perfect government is that which emulates the ordering of the stary vault of Heaven:
{{Quote|To conduct government by virtue may be compared to the North Star: it occupied its place, while the myriad stars revolve around it.|[[Confucius]], ''[[Analects]]'' 2:1}}

==Names and attributes of the God of Heaven in the tradition==
[[File:Tian, god of the square of the north astral pole.svg|thumb|The squared northern [[celestial pole|culmen of the skies]], which is Tian, as a ''[[liubo]]'' board. The ''[[Luo Shu Square|Luoshu]]'' square, the ''[[Yellow River Map|Hetu]]'', ''liubo'' boards, [[sundial]]s, [[Han dynasty|Han]] diviner's boards (''shì'' 式) and ''[[luopan]]'' for ''[[fengshui]]'', and the derived [[compass]], as well as [[TLV mirror]]s, are all representations of the supreme God as the squared north celestial pole.{{sfnb|Didier|2009|p=137 ff, Vol. III}}]]
[[File:Shang grapheme Dì 帝 (Deity) drawn by connecting the Dippers, tying Draco (Tiānlóng 天龙座).svg|thumb|How ''Dì'' 帝 was drawn according to the scholar Pankenier, by connecting the stars [[Gamma Ursae Minoris|γ]], [[Beta Ursae Minoris|β]], and [[5 Ursae Minoris|5]] of the [[Ursa Minor]] (of which the former two are part of the scoop of the Little Dipper) and  [[Zeta Ursae Majoris|ζ]], [[Epsilon Ursae Majoris|ε]], and [[Delta Ursae Majoris|δ]] of the [[Ursa Major]] (and [[Big Dipper]]). Amongst the graphemes containing ''Dì'' there are 締 ''dì'' ("appropriately conjoined" and verbally "to do", "to form"), 諦 ''dì'' ("careful", "attentive", or verbally "to look into", "to examine"), and 蒂 ''dì'' ("calyx", or the "footstalk" that holds a fruit or an inflorescence, which falls and produces other life).{{sfnb|Pankenier|2004|pp=226–236}}{{sfnb|Didier|2009|p=111, Vol. II}} The scholar Didier, otherwise, says that by connecting stars within the same cluster ancient priests-astronomers drew 口 ''Dīng'', the original form of the word ''Dì'' itself, which would represent the supreme God as a square.{{sfnb|Didier|2009|p=216, Vol. I}}]]
{{Quote|Tian is ''dian'' 顛 ("top"), the highest and unexceeded. It derives from the characters ''yi'' 一, "one", and ''da'' 大, "big".{{sfnb|Didier|2009|p=1, Vol. III}}}}
Since the [[Shang dynasty|Shang]] (1600–1046 BCE) and [[Zhou dynasty]] 81046–256 BCE), the radical Chinese terms for the supreme God are ''[[Tian|Tiān]]'' 天 and ''[[Shangdi|Shàngdì]]'' 上帝 (the "Highest Deity") or simply ''Dì'' 帝 ("Deity").{{sfnb|Chang|2000}}{{sfnb|Lü|Gong|2014|pp=63–67}}{{refn|group=note|帝 ''Dì'' is sometimes translated as "[[:wiktionary:thearch|thearch]]", from the Greek ''theos'' ("deity"), with ''[[arche]]'' ("principle", "origin"), thus meaning "divine principle", "divine origin". In sinology it has been used to designate the incarnated gods who, according to Chinese tradition, sustain the world order and originated China.{{sfnb|Pregadio|2013|p=504|ps=: "Each sector of heaven (the four points of the compass and the center) was personified by a ''di'' 帝 (a term which indicates not only an emperor but also an ancestral "thearch" and "god")".}}}} Another concept is ''Tàidì'' 太帝 (the "Great Deity"). These names are combined in different ways in Chinese theological literature, often interchanged in the same paragraph if not in the same sentence.{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|p=66, note 224}} One of the combinations is the name of God used at the [[Temple of Heaven]] in Beijing, which is the "Highest Deity the Heavenly King" (皇天上帝 ''Huángtiān Shàngdì'');{{sfnb|Lü|Gong|2014|p=71}} others are "Great Deity the Heavenly King" (天皇大帝 ''Tiānhuáng Dàdì'') and "Supreme Deity of the Vast Heaven" (昊天上帝 ''Hàotiān Shàngdì'').{{sfnb|Zhong|2014|p=70}}

God is considered manifest in this world as the [[celestial pole|northern culmen and starry vault of the skies]] which regulate nature.{{sfnb|Didier|2009|loc=''passim''}} As its see, the [[circumpolar stars]] (the [[Ursa Minor|Little]] and [[Big Dipper]], or broader Ursa Minor and Ursa Major) are known, among various names, as ''Tiānmén'' 天門 ("Gate of Heaven")<ref name=Reiter>{{cite book|last=Reiter|first=Florian C.|title=Purposes, Means and Convictions in Daoism: A Berlin Symposium|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|year=2007|isbn=3447055138}} p. 190.</ref> and ''Tiānshū'' 天樞 ("Pivot of Heaven"), or the "celestial clock" regulating the four seasons of time.<ref name=Milburn>{{cite book|last=Milburn|first=Olivia|title=The Spring and Autumn Annals of Master Yan|series=Sinica Leidensia|publisher=BRILL|year=2016|isbn=9004309667}} p. 343, note 17.</ref> The Chinese supreme God is compared to the conception of the supreme God identified as the north celestial pole in other cultures, including the [[Mesopotamia]]n ''[[An]]'' ("Heaven" itself), and [[Enlil]] and [[Enki]]/[[Marduk]], the [[historical Vedic religion|Vedic]] [[Indra]] and [[Mitra–Varuna]], the [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] [[Ahura Mazda]],{{sfnb|Didier|2009|p=228, Vol. II; ''passim'' Vol. I}} as well as the ''Dyeus'' of common [[Proto-Indo-European religion]].{{sfnb|Didier|2009|p=82, Vol. I}}

Throughout the Chinese theological literary tradition, the Dipper constellations, and especially the Big Dipper (北斗星 ''Běidǒuxīng'', "Northern Dipper"), also known as Great Chariot, within Ursa Major, are portrayed as the potent symbol of spirit, divinity, or of the [[Wufang Shangdi|activity of the supreme God regulating nature]]. Examples include:
{{Quote|The Dipper is the Deity’s carriage. It revolves about the centre, visiting and regulating each of the four regions. It divides yin from yang, establishes the four seasons, equalises the five elemental phases, deploys the seasonal junctures and angular measures, and determines the various periodicities: all these are tied to the Dipper.|[[Sima Qian]], ''Treatise on the Celestial Officers''{{sfnb|Pankenier|2013|p=9}}}}
{{Quote|When the handle of the Dipper points to the east at dawn, it is spring to all the world. When the handle of the Dipper points to the south it is summer to all the world. When the handle of the Dipper points to the west, it is autumn to all the world. When the handle of the Dipper points to the north, it is winter to all the world. As the handle of the Dipper rotates above, so affairs are set below.|''Heguanzi'', 5:21/1-4{{sfnb|Pankenier|2004|p=220}}}}

''Dì'' is literally a title expressing dominance over the [[Tianxia|all-under-Heaven]], that is all created things.{{sfnb|Lü|Gong|2014|p=64}} It is etymologically and figuratively analogous to the concept of ''di'' as the base of a fruit, which falls and produces other fruits. This analogy is attested in the ''[[Shuowen Jiezi]]'' explaining "deity" as "what faces the base of a melon fruit".{{sfnb|Zhao|2012|p=51}} ''Tiān'' is usually translated as "Heaven", but by graphical etymology it means "Great One" and scholars relate it to the same ''Dì'' through phonetic etymology and trace their common root, through their archaic forms respectively ''*Teeŋ'' and ''*Tees'', to the symbols of the celestial pole and its spinning stars.{{sfnb|Didier|2009|loc=''passim''}} Other words, such as 顶 ''dǐng'' ("on top", "apex") would share the same etymology, all connected to a conceptualisation—according to the scholar John C. Didier—of the north celestial pole godhead as cosmic square (''Dīng'' 口).{{sfnb|Dider|2009|p=4, Vol. III}} Zhou (2005) even connects ''Dì'', through [[Old Chinese]] ''*Tees'' and by phonetic etymology, to the [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''Dyeus''.{{sfnb|Zhou|2005}} Medhurst (1847) also shows affinities in the usage of "deity", Chinese ''di'', Greek ''theos'' and Latin ''deus'', for incarnate powers resembling the supreme godhead.{{sfnb|Medhurst|1847|p=260}}

