'''Efraim Zalmonovich''' is an Orthodox Jewish rabbi known for declaring [[medical cannabis]] to be kosher in 2013.<ref name="jewishjournal1">{{cite web|url=http://jewishjournal.com/tag/efraim-zalmanovich/ |title=Efraim Zalmanovich Archives — Jewish Journal |website=Jewishjournal.com |date=2013-06-28 |accessdate=2017-04-27}}</ref> Zalmanovich is rabbi of [[Mazkeret Batia]], Israel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Surkes |first=Sue |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/rabbi-weed-is-kosher-if-its-medicinal/ |title=Rabbi: Weed is kosher if medicinal |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=2013-06-28 |accessdate=2017-04-27}}</ref>
==Cannabis ruling== In 2013, Zalmonovich issued a [[halahkic]] ruling that consuming recreational cannabis is forbidden, but consuming medical cannabis is a [[mitzvah]]. This ruling was at odds with an earlier ruling by Rabbi [[Hagai Bar Giora]] who earlier in 2013 opined that there is no issue with smoking cannabis.<ref name="jewishjournal1"/> Zalmonovich's views were informed by personal experience: “My mother and sister were diagnosed with cancer and suffered from terrible pain. So I asked the doctors for as much marijuana for them as possible.”<ref name="Malul">{{cite web|last=Malul |first=Chen |url=http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/science/.premium-1.649769 |title=Are cannabis and cigarettes kosher for Passover? - Sites |website=Haaretz.com |date=2015-04-01 |accessdate=2017-04-27}}</ref>
He further noted that cannabis is however not [[chametz]], and that on Jewish holidays where starting a fire is forbidden, one may not strike a flame to ignite cannabis, but it is allowed to light it from a candle already burning, or consume a [[cannabis edible]].<ref name="Malul"/>
